  "prompt": "What is the transpose of a matrix ?",
  "response": "The transpose of a matrix is a new matrix obtained by flipping the original matrix over its diagonal. This means that the rows of the original matrix become the columns in the transposed matrix, and the columns become the rows. \n\nIf \\( A \\) is a matrix, the transpose of \\( A \\) is denoted as \\( A^T \\) or \\( A' \\). If matrix \\( A \\) has dimensions \\( m \\times n \\) (m rows and n columns), its transpose \\( A^T \\) will have dimensions \\( n \\times m \\) (n rows and m columns).\n\nFor example, if we have:\n\n\\[\nA = \\begin{bmatrix}\n1 & 2 & 3 \\\\\n4 & 5 & 6\n\\end{bmatrix}\n\\]\n\nThen the transpose \\( A^T \\) would be:\n\n\\[\nA^T = \\begin{bmatrix}\n1 & 4 \\\\\n2 & 5 \\\\\n3 & 6\n\\end{bmatrix}\n\\]\n\nIn general, if the element at position \\( (i, j) \\) in matrix \\( A \\) is \\( a_{ij} \\), then the element at position \\( (j, i) \\) in the transposed matrix \\( A^T \\) is also \\( a_{ij} \\). In other words, \n\n\\[\n(A^T)_{ji} = A_{ij}\n\\]",
